[[File:Seeds of ' Meiogyne cylindrocarpa' - 2014-02-26 17-14.jpg|thumbnail|Seeds of fingersop (''Meiogyne cylindrocarpa'' subsp. ''cylindrocarpa'')]]

Fingersop is typically [[Plant propagation|propagated]] by seeds, taking anywhere from two weeks to six months to [[germinate]]. Plant seeds about a quarter inch deep in moist, well drained soil, and do not allow to dry out, the [[embryos]] are rather small and are encased in a thick [[seed]]coat, so a small amount of mold in the younger stages can be [[beneficial]] for faster germination. [[Seedlings]] of ''M. c.'' subsp. ''cylindrocarpa'' tend to be smaller, with a [[bush (plant)|bush]]ier form then ''M. c.'' subsp. ''trichocarpa'', which is more [[tree|erect]]. Trees [[angiosperms|bear fruit]] after five to six years, but when [[grafting|grafted]], will produce much sooner and develop a smaller, more compact form.

